❄️ Does the winter wreak havoc on your skin? The harsh, cold air is the cause of dry, flaky skin for many Minnesotans each year.

Here are Dr. Tareen’s TOP 3 tips for keeping your skin happy and hydrated in the colder months. 

TIP 1 - Swap a foaming cleanser out for a creamy one!
TIP 2 - Try a thick moisturizing cream instead of a thin lotion
TIP 3 - Always wear you sunscreen! Although most people think of summer as the time for sunscreen, wearing it in the winter is just as important! The sun’s rays are amplified when they reflect off of snow – causing all sorts of damage to the skin.

BONUS TIPS!  Wear a scarf that covers your face from harsh winds and run a humidifier in your bedroom at night!

What is a dermatofibroma? ▫️ Read below! ⬇️

Dermatofibromas are benign skin growths that often appear from minor trauma to the skin. They are commonly found on the arms and legs, are generally harmless, but occasionally get irritated from clothing. This patient’s dermatofibroma was located on the back of her calf and likely from a past bug bite. It was bothersome when shaving, so it was time to remove it. 🪒 

🧊 Using cryotherapy - also known as liquid nitrogen this bothersome spot was frozen off! ❄️ In just a few weeks, the area scabbed over and healed beautifully. 

🔹 Although dermatofibromas are usually harmless, they can be similar in appearance to other more concerning skin tumours. That’s why it’s important to get your skin evaluated by a board-certified provider for an official diagnosis

🔹What is CO2 Laser?
Fractionated Co2 Pixel Laser Resurfacing improves the appearance of skin by affecting only a fraction of it at a time using thousands of tiny microscopic laser spots. The Pixel laser light passes through an optic lens into the skin with tiny channels of heat. Healthy skin around each of these channels heals quickly and spreads over the tiny holes. The heat produced by the laser light tightens the skin and in turn softens wrinkles, smooths texture, and scars, and minimizes pores while stimulating the skin’s natural collagen production. With CO2 Laser, you will see healthier, firmer, smoother skin with minimal downtime.

🔹What is SkinPen?
SkinPen is the only FDA-approved dermal device for skin tightening. It uses fine needles to penetrate the skin, creating tiny micro-injuries. SkinPen activates the skin’s natural healing process to produce more collagen; a special type of protein that gives skin its elasticity. Our skin slowly loses collagen as we age - this treatment is perfect for all skin types!

🔹What is Keralase?
Keralase treatments utilize our Lutronic LaseMD Ultra laser to create microchannels in the scalp. Following the treatment, a high-impact growth factor serum is massaged into these microchannels to stimulate hair growth. What is #Sclerotherapy? It’s a quick, non-surgical treatment we offer here at our clinic to treat spider veins. 🙌

💉 Sclerotherapy helps to eliminate unsightly varicose veins and spider veins with no downtime. It involves an injection of an FDA-approved solution directly into the vein’s lining (blood vessel), causing it to collapse and stick together. Over time, the treated blood vessels turn to scar tissue, and they fade away! 👋 

With Dr. Tareen’s precise injections, you will see the veins disappear right before your eyes which is oh so #satisfying! 😌

Did you hear First Lady, Jill Biden, will undergo Mohs surgery to remove a small lesion on her face? Found during a routine skin cancer screening, the small lesion above her eye will be removed using a procedure we offer right here at Tareen Dermatology! 

☕️ Over their morning coffee, Dr. Tareen and Hannah Dahl PA-C went over what the procedure is. 🥼

▪️ Mohs surgery is a highly effective way of removing skin cancers. Once a tissue layer is removed, the edges are marked with specially colored dyes, and a map of the specimen is created.

🔬 The tissue is then processed and carefully examined under the microscope so that any microscopic roots of the cancer can be precisely identified and mapped.

When cancer cells are seen, an additional tissue layer is removed only in areas where the cancer is still present, leaving normal skin intact. This saves as much normal, healthy skin as possible - so is a great option for skin cancers on the face. Once the cancer has been removed, the Dr. Tareen explains options for repair of the wound, including natural healing (granulation), stitching the wound together by a side to side closure, or using a skin flap or graft.

Can melanoma be white? 🤔 Read below! 👇

Real Housewives of Beverly Hills star, Teddi Mellencamp, was declared cancer-free last year after having multiple skin lesions removed. She recently went in for a follow up and had a few more biopsies taken due to more suspicious areas. Although melanoma is typically shades of brown, black, or tan, in some cases they can appear pink, red, blue, or white as they grow. In her case, her doctors did not want to take the risk.

Another skin condition, known as idiopathic guttate hypomelanosis (IGH) may be similar in appearance, but the official diagnosis is determined under a microscope.

In an Instagram post, Teddi noted the importance of “staying on top of my appointments, self-checks, and asking my doctors questions”. We are sending strength to Teddi on her journey and applaud her for sharing her story while spreading #MelanomaAwareness

When it comes to your moles, use the ABCDEs of Melanoma to help determine the warning signs.

🔹A🔹 ASYMMETRY
One half does not match the other

🔹 B 🔹 BORDER
The edges are irregular, notched, or blurred.

🔹 C 🔹 COLOR
The mole has more than one color.

🔹 D 🔹 DIAMETER
The mole is larger than an eraser (6mm) across.

🔹 E🔹 EVOLVING
There are changes in shape, size, and color.

If you’ve experienced a change in any of the above indicators, please schedule an appointment with one of our providers as soon as possible. 🫶

Do you use a retinol? 🤔 

👇 Remember these 3 tips if you do! ✨

1️⃣ Start low + slow! First time retinol users may experience reactions. When you’re just starting out, use a small, low dose amount once or twice a week to see how your skin reacts. Gradually work up to every other day or three times a week. Stick to formulas with 1% retinol or less unless your dermatologist prescribes more. Beginners should start with 0.25% and then increase slowly to 0.5 and then to 1.0 overtime. 

2️⃣ Use retinol at night. Retinol makes your skin more sensitive to sunlight, so it’s extremely import to use your SPF the next morning!

3️⃣ Don’t mix with certain actives like vitamin C, benzoyl peroxide, and AHA/BHA acids. AHA and BHA acids are exfoliating, which can dry out the skin and cause further irritation.

Retinols are Vitamin A derivatives that help to speed up skin cell turnover – and in the process, help to smooth the skin, reduce fine lines and wrinkles, and help with acne and pigmentation!

Fractionated Co2 Pixel Laser Resurfacing improves the appearance of skin by affecting only a fraction of it at a time using thousands of tiny microscopic laser spots. The Pixel laser light passes through an optic lens into the skin with tiny channels of heat. Healthy skin around each of these channels heals quickly and spreads over the tiny holes. The heat produced by the laser light tightens the skin and in turn softens wrinkles, smooths texture, and scars, and minimizes pores while stimulating the skin’s natural collagen production. With CO2 Laser, you will see healthier, firmer, smoother skin with minimal downtime.

The mole is larger than a pencil eraser (6mm) across.

There are changes in shape, size, and color.

🍋 Citrus Fruits - (Especially Limes, Lemons, + Pomelos)
🌿 Wild Parsley

Do you experience excessive sweating? 🥵

Abnormal excessive sweating is referred to as hyperhidrosis. It can be diffused throughout the body, especially in the hands, feet, face, and underarms. 

Hyperhidrosis is common, and there are many treatment options to suppress it. 

1. Topical solutions: prescriptions that are applied to the body, like aluminum chloride. 🧴
2. Oral medications: halt sweat production from the sweat glands. 💊
3. Iontophoresis: electric currents are passed through the sweat glands and suppress their activity. We recommend @dermadry as an iontophoresis device. ⚡️
4. Botox or Dysport injections: diminishes sweat production from the sweat glands, and effects can last 6-9 months. This treatment kicks into effect around 2 weeks. 💉
5. Liposuction and laser treatments: used to injure the sweat glands under the skin and diminish their activity. 🕶️
6. Surgical: cutting the nerve that activates the sweat glands. This procedure is reserved for extreme cases. ✂️

Recent studies have shown that hyperhidrosis is strongly associated with depression and anxiety. Don’t let this dull your shine! Schedule an appointment with a dermatologist who can help!

What is a lipoma? A lipoma is a lump of tissue made of fat that grows beneath the skin. It’s unclear why they develop, but you are more likely to develop one if it’s passed down through your family. It’s common to find them in the neck, back, shoulders, arms, thighs, and abdomen.

While these bumps under your skin can be scary, lipomas are more than likely harmless. Rarely, they can be cancerous. However, they still need to be checked by your dermatologist. 🔎

Treatment generally is not necessary, but if the lipoma is painful or growing, it may need to be surgically removed. Lucky for you, we provide great care. Give us a call if you need your skin checked out!

Are you on your last strand with your hair? ✂️

Before introducing it to another new product or chopping it off, try letting your hair tell you what it needs. Perform a Hair Porosity Water Test! (Don’t worry; there are no wrong answers, and it takes less than 15 minutes.)

Hair porosity is the hair’s ability to retain and absorb moisture. With this test, you should be able to tell if your hair is damaged, in need of moisture, or is balanced and healthy.

👇 Here’s the result breakdown:

Low Porosity Hair: the hair strand floats. This type of hair has cuticles that are bound close together. Your hair needs moisture! 💧

Normal Porosity Hair: the hair strand floats and then sinks slowly. This type of hair has cuticles that are looser. Your hair is perfect! Use a deep conditioner to maintain its health. ✨

High Porosity Hair: the hair strand sinks immediately. This type of hair has a raised porous cuticle. Your hair can’t retain water! Try to stay away from hair-damaging factors like hair dye, sun, and chlorine. 🌵

What is Cauliflower Ear, really? 👂🏽

Cauliflower ear occurs from blunt trauma to the outer ear. Blood and other fluids fill in that space between the skin and cartilage. The skin on the surface of the ear is the only blood supply for cartilage. Without blood flow, the cartilage is starved of its nutrients and the tissue hardens. If the injury is ignored by not being drained properly, the ear results in a deformity.

Common causes of these injuries are from sports, such as wrestling, boxing, or mixed martial arts. In these sports, there can be hard or repeated hits to the ear that lead to hematomas. Hematomas are small collections of blood that clot and block the flow of nutrients and blood. 🩸

Seek professional help immediately if you have concerns about cauliflower ear. Deformities become permanent in about 7-10 days!

Carrot Tan or Orange Scam? 🥕

A popular beauty trend on TikTok claims that eating 3 carrots a day will give you a natural tan. Is the “carrot tan” true?

Carrots CAN give a yellow/orange pigment to the skin. How does this happen? Beta-carotene is responsible for making carrots bright orange. When digested, cells in the gut break the beat-carotene into two molecules of retinol (or vitamin A). When the body has enough vitamin A, it stops converting beta-carotene into vitamin A, and any extra is stored in the liver and fat tissue or removed via sweat or feces. This is when “carrot tan” can happen.🍊

Carotenoderma is the term when referring to skin turning a yellow/orange pigment. Eating three carrots a day will not give you a natural tan but a subtle orange tint to your skin. A natural tan is the increase of production of melanin when exposed to UV radiation.

Do you have irregular scarring? You may have a keloid.☝️

A keloid is an overgrowth of scar tissue. Keloid growth can be triggered by any skin injury. Body piercings, burns, hair removal, insect bites, acne, and more can all cause a type of raised scar known as a keloid. 🤕

Keloids form from collagen. Collagen is a protein found throughout the body that is useful for healing wounds. When the body produces too much, this is when keloids can form.

Keloids can grow very fast. This is why it’s important to take action immediately if it’s desired by the patient or recommended by a professional.🥼

Do you have strawberry or chicken skin? 🍓🐔

Keratosis Pilaris (KP), also known as strawberry or chicken skin, is a skin condition that causes rough patches and small bumps on the skin. The condition develops when too much of a protein called keratin is produced, which can block hair follicles and cause bumps to develop.

Common treatments in the U.S. are as follows: topical creams that include alpha hydroxy acids (AHAs) such as lactic acid, glycolic acid, salicylic acid, or urea. 🫧

KP cannot be cured, so you will need to follow a maintenance plan. If it remains despite at-home treatments, a dermatologist can help. 👍🏽
